SIMPLE: march
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: March
<hw>March</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧rch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Martius
mensis</ets> Mars'month fr. <ets>Martius</ets> belonging to
<ets>Mars</ets>, the god of war: cf. F. <ets>mars</ets>. Cf.
<er>Martial</er>.]</ety> <def>The third month of the year, containing
thirty-one days.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stormy <qex>March</qex> is come at last,⟦br⟧
With wind, and cloud, and changing skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>As mad as a March Hare</b></col>, <cd>an old English
Saying derived from the fact that March is the rutting time of hares,
when they are excitable and violent.</cd>
<rj><au>Wright.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: March
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marche</ets>, F.
<ets>marche</ets>; of German origin; cf. OHG. <ets>marcha</ets>, G.
<ets>mark</ets>, akin to OS. <ets>marka</ets>, AS. <ets>mearc</ets>,
Goth. <ets>marka</ets>, L. <ets>margo</ets> edge, border, margin, and
possibly to E. <ets>mark</ets> a sign. ⟦root⟧106. Cf. <er>Margin</er>,
<er>Margrave</er>, <er>Marque</er>, <er>Marquis</er>.]</ety> <def>A
territorial border or frontier; a region adjacent to a boundary line; a
confine; -- used chiefly in the plural, and in English history applied
especially to the border land on the frontiers between England and
Scotland, and England and Wales.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Geneva is situated in the <qex>marches</qex> of several dominions
-- France, Savoy, and Switzerland.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lords of waste <qex>marches</qex>, kings of desolate isles.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: March
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>marchir</ets>. See
2d <er>March</er>.]</ety> <def>To border; to be contiguous; to lie side
by side.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That was in a strange land⟦br⟧
Which <qex>marcheth</qex> upon Chimerie.</q>
<rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To march with</b></col>, <cd>to have the same boundary
for a greater or less distance; -- said of an estate.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: March
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Marched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Marching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>marcher</ets>, in OF.
also, to tread, prob. fr. L. <ets>marcus</ets> hammer. Cf.
<er>Mortar</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move with regular steps, as
a soldier; to walk in a grave, deliberate, or stately manner; to advance
steadily.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To proceed by walking in a body or in military
order; <as>as, the German army <er>marched</er> into
France</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: March
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to move with regular
steps in the manner of a soldier; to cause to move in military array, or
in a body, as troops; to cause to advance in a steady, regular, or
stately manner; to cause to go by peremptory command, or by
force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>March</qex> them again in fair array.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: March
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marche</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of marching; a movement of soldiers from one
stopping place to another; military progress; advance of
troops.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These troops came to the army harassed with a long and wearisome
<qex>march</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Measured and regular advance or movement,
like that of soldiers moving in order; stately or deliberate walk;
steady onward movement; <as>as, the <ex>march</ex> of
time</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With solemn <qex>march</qex>⟦br⟧
Goes slow and stately by them.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This happens merely because men will not bide their time, but will
insist on precipitating the <qex>march</qex> of affairs.</q>
<rj><qau>Buckle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The distance passed over in marching; <as>as, an
hour's <ex>march</ex>; a <ex>march</ex> of twenty miles.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A piece of music designed or fitted to accompany and
guide the movement of troops; a piece of music in the march
form.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The drums presently striking up a <qex>march</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make a march</b></col>, <fld>(Card Playing)</fld>,
<cd>to take all the tricks of a hand, in the game of
euchre.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marchand de vin</ent>⟦br⟧
